<h2 style="font-family: 'Roboto', sans-serif;">What are Mini Neptune Exoplanets?</h2>

<p>Mini Neptunes are a class of exoplanets that are smaller and less massive than Neptune but larger than Earth. These
    planets, often composed of a rocky core surrounded by a substantial hydrogen-helium atmosphere, occupy an intriguing
    middle ground between terrestrial planets and gas giants. They are frequently found in other solar systems, orbiting
    stars in a wide variety of environments. Mini Neptunes can provide valuable insights into planetary formation and
    evolution, particularly in understanding the transition from rocky super-Earths to larger, gaseous planets. The
    study of Mini Neptunes is critical as they represent one of the most common types of planets in our galaxy,
    potentially hosting atmospheres with complex chemistry.
</p>
