        </li>

        <li><strong>Surface Conditions</strong>:If the atmosphere of GJ 1214 b is genuinely water-rich, the surface
            conditions might be similar to a steam bath, but much hotter than anything found on Earth or any other
            planet in our solar system.</li>

        <li><strong>Water World Scenario</strong>:Given the possibility of a sizable water content, GJ 1214 b may
            resemble an ocean planet rather than a typical gas giant, providing a novel viewpoint on the idea of
            habitability in harsh environments.</li>

        <li><strong>Host Star</strong>: Its mass is estimated to be four times that of Uranus, suggesting a
            substantial build-up of mass from either an expanded disc or material captured from its surroundings.</li>

        <li><strong>Research Potential</strong>:Its discovery supports the hypothesis that these planets may form
            closer to their stars before migrating outward and offers insights into the genesis of ice giants.​​</li>
    </ol>
